### Original Comments

#### Feedback Bot on 4/21/2026, 00:57 AM: 

<p>Thank you for taking the time to provide your suggestion. We will do some preliminary checks to make sure we can proceed further. You will hear from us in about a week on our next steps.</p>

## Background and Motivation

Today, Blazor's entire form validation pipeline is synchronous. `EditContext.Validate()` fires a synchronous `OnValidationRequested` event and returns `bool`. Developers who need async validation - such as database uniqueness checks, remote API calls, or service-based business rule validation - have to block on async operations using `.Result` or `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`, which is incompatible with Blazor WebAssembly and causes deadlocks on Blazor Server. The upcoming async APIs in `System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations`, as well as third-party libraries like FluentValidation, cannot fully integrate with Blazor's `EditContext` because the event model is synchronous.

Unlike synchronous validation, async validation introduces a period where the outcome is unknown. The UI needs to communicate this to users (spinners, disabling submit) and distinguish infrastructure failures from validation errors - requiring the framework to expose per-field pending and faulted state.

This proposal adds:

- An async event (`OnValidationRequestedAsync`) for validator components to subscribe to.
- `EditContext.ValidateAsync(CancellationToken)` - an async counterpart to the existing sync `Validate()`.
- Per-field async validation task tracking via `EditContext.AddValidationTask(...)`, with framework-managed cancellation and supersession.
- Programmatic state queries (`IsValidationPending`, `IsValidationFaulted`) - per-field and form-level overloads - for UI feedback.

The existing sync `Validate()` is kept and extended to invoke async handlers as well, throwing `InvalidOperationException` if any returns an incomplete `Task` so async validators can never be silently skipped.

Issue: [dotnet/aspnetcore#7680](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/7680).

## Proposed API

### 1. Async validation event and method on `EditContext`

```diff
 namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Forms;

 public sealed class EditContext
 {
     // Existing sync event - unchanged.
     public event EventHandler<ValidationRequestedEventArgs>? OnValidationRequested;

+    /// <summary>
+    /// Async event raised when validation is requested. Validator components subscribe
+    /// to perform async validation (e.g., database lookups, remote API calls). For a given
+    /// source of validation, subscribe to either OnValidationRequested or
+    /// OnValidationRequestedAsync, not both. All handlers are invoked and awaited by
+    /// ValidateAsync.
+    /// </summary>
+    public event Func<object, ValidationRequestedEventArgs, Task>? OnValidationRequestedAsync;

     // Existing sync method - extended to also invoke OnValidationRequestedAsync handlers
     // and throw InvalidOperationException if any returns an incomplete Task. Sync-only
     // validators keep working unchanged.
     public bool Validate();

+    /// <summary>
+    /// Validates this EditContext asynchronously. Cancels any pending field-level validation
+    /// tasks, invokes both sync OnValidationRequested and async OnValidationRequestedAsync
+    /// handlers, and returns whether the model is valid. The cancellation token is surfaced to
+    /// handlers via ValidationRequestedEventArgs.CancellationToken and bounds the in-flight
+    /// pass only.
+    /// </summary>
+    public Task<bool> ValidateAsync(CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);
 }
```

`OnValidationRequestedAsync` is declared as `event Func<object, ValidationRequestedEventArgs, Task>?` so multiple validator components on the same form can subscribe and run concurrently. `ValidateAsync` retrieves the handlers via `GetInvocationList()` and awaits them all via `Task.WhenAll`.

`ValidateAsync` semantics:

- Cancels all in-flight per-field tasks at the start of the pass (form-submit validation supersedes them).
- Raises `OnValidationRequested` synchronously; sync exceptions propagate to the caller (same as `Validate()`).
- Raises `OnValidationRequestedAsync` and awaits all handlers concurrently.
- If the caller's `cancellationToken` trips, rethrows `OperationCanceledException`. The previous form-level fault flag is preserved (no new outcome was produced).
- A non-cancellation exception from any async handler is contained: the form-level fault flag is set to `true`, and the method returns `false`.
- Otherwise returns `!GetValidationMessages().Any()`.

`Validate()` is kept (not marked `[Obsolete]`) and extended:

1. Raises `OnValidationRequested`. Sync exceptions propagate.
2. Invokes each `OnValidationRequestedAsync` handler in turn; if the returned `Task` is not yet completed, throws `InvalidOperationException` directing the caller to `ValidateAsync()`. Otherwise calls `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` to surface any synchronous fault.
3. Returns `!GetValidationMessages().Any()`.

### 2. Per-field async task tracking

```diff
 namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Forms;

 public sealed class EditContext
 {
+    /// <summary>
+    /// Registers an in-flight async validation task for a specific field. If a task is
+    /// already tracked for the field, the prior CancellationTokenSource is cancelled and
+    /// the new task replaces it. EditContext takes ownership of the supplied CTS and
+    /// disposes it when the task settles.
+    /// </summary>
+    public void AddValidationTask(
+        in FieldIdentifier fieldIdentifier,
+        Task task,
+        CancellationTokenSource cts);
 }
```

`AddValidationTask` is the entry point validator components use to register an async per-field validation. Each field has at most one tracked slot. The contract:

- A new `AddValidationTask` for the same field cancels the prior slot's CTS before installing the new one. The framework's observer takes care of disposing the prior CTS when the prior task settles, so a validator can never observe a disposed token.
- A task that is already completed at registration time is settled synchronously: a faulted completed task surfaces field-level fault directly; a successful or cancelled completed task is a no-op.
- A faulted task (non-`OperationCanceledException`) sets the field's `IsValidationFaulted` flag. Cancellation is silent.
- `ValidateAsync()` cancels every per-field CTS at the start of each form-level pass and also clears any lingering `IsValidationFaulted` flag, so each form-level pass starts from a clean per-field baseline.

### 3. Pending and faulted state queries

```diff
 namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Forms;

 public sealed class EditContext
 {
+    // Per-field: returns true while a tracked async validation task is in flight for the
+    // field. The slot is cleared by the framework's observer once the task settles, so a
+    // consumer that waits for IsValidationPending to become false is guaranteed to also
+    // see the final IsValidationFaulted value.
+    public bool IsValidationPending(in FieldIdentifier fieldIdentifier);
+    public bool IsValidationPending<TField>(Expression<Func<TField>> accessor);
+
+    // Form-level: returns true only while a ValidateAsync() pass is currently in flight.
+    // Suitable for driving form-wide UI such as disabling submit; not a union over per-field
+    // state.
+    public bool IsValidationPending();
+
+    // Per-field: returns true if the field's last async validation threw a
+    // non-cancellation exception.
+    public bool IsValidationFaulted(in FieldIdentifier fieldIdentifier);
+    public bool IsValidationFaulted<TField>(Expression<Func<TField>> accessor);
+
+    // Form-level: returns true if the most recent ValidateAsync() pass observed an
+    // unhandled handler exception. Set at completion; preserved across caller-cancelled
+    // passes.
+    public bool IsValidationFaulted();
 }
```

The expression-based overloads (`IsValidationPending<TField>(Expression<Func<TField>>)`, `IsValidationFaulted<TField>(Expression<Func<TField>>)`) match the existing `ValidationMessage.For` syntax so per-field state can be queried with `editContext.IsValidationPending(() => model.Username)`.

The parameterless form-level overloads are deliberately separate from a union of per-field state. Splitting them lets apps build a "submit button disabled while submit-validation runs" indicator without flickering on every keystroke that triggers a per-field task, and vice versa.

### 4. Cancellation token on `ValidationRequestedEventArgs`

```diff
 namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Forms;

 public sealed class ValidationRequestedEventArgs : EventArgs
 {
+    /// <summary>
+    /// Creates a new instance carrying a cancellation token to surface to async handlers.
+    /// </summary>
+    public ValidationRequestedEventArgs(CancellationToken cancellationToken);
+
+    /// <summary>
+    /// Token signalled when the caller of ValidateAsync requests cancellation.
+    /// Synchronous handlers can ignore this; async handlers that perform long-running work
+    /// (database lookups, remote API calls) should pass it to their downstream APIs.
+    /// </summary>
+    public CancellationToken CancellationToken { get; }
 }
```

When the caller passes a non-default token, `ValidateAsync` constructs a new `ValidationRequestedEventArgs` carrying it; otherwise it reuses the shared `ValidationRequestedEventArgs.Empty` instance (with `CancellationToken.None`). The token bounds the in-flight pass only - per-field tasks started independently during the awaited window are not linked to it.

### Behavioral changes that are not new public API

These changes are observable but do not add or modify public method signatures:

- **`EditForm.HandleSubmitAsync()` now calls `EditContext.ValidateAsync()` instead of `Validate()`.** Forms using `OnValidSubmit` / `OnInvalidSubmit` automatically benefit - `OnValidSubmit` only fires after async validators have settled. Forms using `OnSubmit` continue to call `Validate()` or migrate to `await context.ValidateAsync()` at the developer's discretion.
- **`FieldCssClassProvider.GetFieldCssClass` returns two additional CSS-class values:** `"pending"` (and `"modified pending"`) while `IsValidationPending(field)` is `true`, and `"faulted"` (and `"modified faulted"`) while `IsValidationFaulted(field)` is `true`. These supersede `"valid"`/`"invalid"` because neither outcome is known yet. Custom `FieldCssClassProvider` subclasses can override this to map the new states to framework-specific class names (e.g. Bootstrap's `is-validating`).
- **Built-in `DataAnnotationsValidator` routing.** `DataAnnotationsEventSubscriptions` subscribes only to `OnValidationRequestedAsync` (and `OnFieldChanged`). The async handler routes internally based on whether the model has an `IValidatableInfo` registered via `Microsoft.Extensions.Validation`: if yes, validation runs through `IValidatableInfo.ValidateAsync` (allowing async attributes); if no, it falls back to synchronous `Validator.TryValidateObject` and the returned `Task` completes synchronously (which is why `Validate()` keeps working for sync-only models). Per-field async validation on the MEV path uses `ValidationOptions.TryGetValidatablePropertyInfo` (proposed separately).

## Usage Examples

### Implicit submit validation

No code change required for forms that already use `OnValidSubmit`. `EditForm` internally calls `ValidateAsync()`:

```razor
<EditForm Model="registration" OnValidSubmit="HandleValidSubmit">
    <DataAnnotationsValidator />
    <InputText @bind-Value="registration.Username" />
    <button type="submit">Register</button>
    <ValidationSummary />
</EditForm>

@code {
    private async Task HandleValidSubmit(EditContext context)
    {
        // Only fires after ALL validation (including async) has passed.
        await UserService.CreateAsync(registration);
    }
}
```

### Explicit submit validation

Apps using `OnSubmit` call `ValidateAsync()`:

```razor
@code {
    private async Task HandleSubmit(EditContext context)
    {
        if (await context.ValidateAsync())
        {
            await UserService.CreateAsync(registration);
        }
    }
}
```

### Per-field pending and faulted UI

The expression-based overloads match `ValidationMessage` syntax:

```razor
<InputText @bind-Value="registration.Username" />

@if (editContext.IsValidationPending(() => registration.Username))
{
    <span class="spinner">Checking availability…</span>
}
else if (editContext.IsValidationFaulted(() => registration.Username))
{
    <span>An error occurred while validating. Please try again.</span>
}
else
{
    <ValidationMessage For="() => registration.Username" />
}
```

### Third-party validator integration

Library authors subscribe to the async event for form-submit validation and use `AddValidationTask` for per-field tracking:

```csharp
public class FluentValidationValidator : ComponentBase
{
    [CascadingParameter] EditContext EditContext { get; set; } = default!;

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        EditContext.OnValidationRequestedAsync += async (sender, args) =>
        {
            var validator = GetValidatorForModel(EditContext.Model);
            var result = await validator.ValidateAsync(EditContext.Model, args.CancellationToken);
            // Populate ValidationMessageStore with results
        };

        EditContext.OnFieldChanged += (sender, args) =>
        {
            var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
            var task = RunFieldValidationAsync(args.FieldIdentifier, cts.Token);
            EditContext.AddValidationTask(args.FieldIdentifier, task, cts);
        };
    }
}
```

## Alternative Designs

**Mark `Validate()` as `[Obsolete]` instead of extending it.** Marking the sync `Validate()` obsolete with a message pointing at `ValidateAsync()` would give callers a compile-time signal to migrate. Rejected because (1) `EditContext.Validate()` has shipped for many releases and is referenced by every existing Blazor form sample and tutorial; an obsolete warning would generate noise in every existing app, including those that use only sync validators and don't need to change; and (2) the extended behavior achieves the same outcome (`Validate()` keeps working for sync models and throws loudly for async ones), so apps with async validators get a runtime exception pointing at `ValidateAsync` instead of silent skipping.

**Optional `syncOnly` parameter on `Validate()` (`bool Validate(bool syncOnly = false)`).** This would preserve `Validate()` as a non-obsolete API for intentional sync-only validation, even on models that have async validators registered. Rejected because the existing `Validate()` already serves that role for sync-only models (it throws only when an async handler returns an incomplete `Task`), and adding a parameter that means "ignore the configured async validators" creates a footgun where developers may accidentally bypass validation that the model author intended to be applied.

**Declarative UI for per-field pending and faulted state.** `ValidationMessage` could grow `PendingContent` and `FaultedContent` render fragment parameters that the component renders in place of the error list while the field is in those states. Deferred because (1) `ValidationMessage` currently does not accept child content - it renders a flat list of `<div class="validation-message">` elements - so adding render fragments would be a change to its rendering contract; (2) the programmatic `IsValidationPending` / `IsValidationFaulted` queries together with the new `"pending"`/`"faulted"` CSS classes are sufficient for the initial release; and (3) a separate `<ValidationStatus>` component is a viable alternative that can be added as a follow-up without breaking `ValidationMessage`.

**`ValidateFieldAsync(FieldIdentifier)` on `EditContext`.** A dedicated method to re-validate a single field on demand (without simulating an edit via `NotifyFieldChanged`, which has the side effect of flipping `IsModified`). Deferred to a follow-up so we can validate the broader API surface first. The current shape is sufficient for the common cases - validators that own per-field validation can re-run it themselves via `AddValidationTask` from a "retry" button.

## Risks

- **`IValidationLocalizer` and `EditContext.Validate()` interaction.** Apps that rely on the sync `Validate()` to drive validation and also depend on per-field validation state mutating during the call now get a `false`/`true` answer that may also include the outcome of `OnValidationRequestedAsync` handlers (if they completed synchronously). This is a minor observable change in the order of state notifications during `Validate()`; existing fully-sync validator components are unaffected.
- **CSS class `"pending"`/`"faulted"` not appearing in user stylesheets.** Apps with custom CSS that styles `.modified.valid` / `.modified.invalid` will not get any styling for the new `pending`/`faulted` states unless they add rules for them. This is a minor doc/migration item, not a correctness issue.
- **Per-field task ownership.** `AddValidationTask` takes ownership of the supplied `CancellationTokenSource`. Validator authors who reuse a `CancellationTokenSource` across calls or dispose it themselves will see incorrect behavior. The XML doc states the ownership contract explicitly.

Fixes #66877

**Problem**

OutputCacheMiddleware can cache an empty or truncated response when the request that populates the cache is canceled. The broken entry is then served to all subsequent clients until it expires.

This happens because the existing cacheability checks have two blind spots:

The Content-Length check is bypassed when the header is absent (e.g. ResponseCompression removes it).

A decorator stream layered above OutputCacheStream (e.g. GZipStream) can throw OperationCanceledException before the write reaches OutputCacheStream, so BufferingEnabled stays true even though the body is incomplete.

The locking path (SetLocking(true)) has an additional issue: concurrent requests waiting on the in-flight response are served directly from the OutputCacheEntry returned by ExecuteResponseAsync, bypassing the normal cacheability checks entirely.

**Fix**

Two targeted changes to OutputCacheMiddleware.cs:

1. FinalizeCacheBodyAsync — skip storing if RequestAborted is canceled:

```csharp
// Do not cache a response whose originating request was aborted.
if (context.HttpContext.RequestAborted.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    _logger.ResponseNotCached();
    return;
}
```

This is the right place because it is the single choke-point before every StoreAsync call. RequestAborted being canceled at this point is a strong, observable signal that the response body is incomplete — it is the token passed to WriteAsync in virtually every IActionResult implementation, and callers are expected to call httpContext.Abort() after catching OperationCanceledException mid-write.

2. ExecuteResponseAsync (locking path) — return null if the request was aborted after _next completes:

```csharp
if (httpContext.RequestAborted.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    _logger.ResponseNotCached();
    return null;
}
```

Returning null here causes TryServeCachedResponseAsync to short-circuit, so no truncated entry is handed off to waiting concurrent requests.

**Testing**

The existing test FinalizeCacheBody_Cache_IfContentLengthAbsent and the locking tests continue to pass unchanged. The repro from the issue (OutputCache + ResponseCompression, client cancels after 1 s, subsequent request should get full payload) is the end-to-end verification scenario.

